This started shortly after Jeremy became leader, and colleagues who, as far as I knew, had a similar political view as I did, suddenly expected me to turn around and take a position that I would never otherwise have agreed to, from issues such as national security to the European single market.
Whenever I speak for an audience, whatever I say, there are social media insults calling for the rejection of my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election, blaming the centre's policies and telling me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who are dealing with a flood of sexist or racist reactions every day, but do not allow themselves to be intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that serious insults are apparently considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church and with every ‘motion of distrust’ or change of selection rules, the party becomes pettyr.
Over the past two years, I have often been advised to keep myself informed, not just to express my opinion out loud and then I wouldn’t ‘get into trouble’.
But I didn’t go into politics for that.
Since I joined Labour 32 years ago as a schoolchild, provoked by the neglect of Thatcher’s government that literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated for better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a city councillor and in my role as a minister.
I never hid my politics, not even in the last election.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy stances and my points of contention with current leadership.
To those who have propagated the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country is dragging itself into a Brexit that will hurt families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in fact, I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election will follow me or political opportunities will not stop me from doing what you are doing.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
