John Edward: Language Skills Essential for Global Citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent state of service in the field of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with again a series of excellent exam results, and in addition individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With more than 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects ideally within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can deduce that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 percent of students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as highly skilled as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that of the obstacles to filling vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
Now that more and more job vacancies require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive edge.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation. French was the only language that stood out above the 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is important for children today.
Being able to speak several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who specialize in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot currently be denied that languages remain vital for the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered as ‘international communication skills.’
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
