Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the US leader said at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party on this issue was South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be an implicit one.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different than last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles would be aimed at the American mainland after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocketman” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to completely destroy North Korea, praised Kim this year at the United Nations for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much still needs to happen and that sanctions should continue until North Korea denuclearizes.
