Harvard students take a course on the importance of sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night long and drink plenty of caffeine.
One professor noted that students from the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course, which, as far as he knows, is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing this now, in my final year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being organized for the first time this year, will explain to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students during the week had a severe sleep deficit.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise devices and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behaviour of the students.
But we think they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what impacts the choice of cigarettes has on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of night-studying pride still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course because he had attended the professor’s class last year when he was in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to get up. They also need to be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronics screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
