He complained that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class had yet been available to be included in the navy.
The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
New research conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, which is being conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large-breasted bat, and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NTS and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's cries and what kind of thing does.
A map of the habitat and a report are then produced to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser at the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making pastures and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Measles populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly in the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, just like flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by house cats.
Butterflies are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly examine, inspect dormitories and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten bat species live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats,” he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats, and that’s why the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of controlling bats before maintenance is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a dormant area can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially eradicating a full local population.
Flea mice are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and from many of our species we simply don’t know how it’s going with their populations.”
