How the U.S.-China trade war can turn out beneficial for Beijing
The opening salvos of the U.S.-China trade war were ear-numbing, and although the fight has not yet been fought, a gap between the two countries could, according to experts, bridge long-term benefits for Beijing.
U.S. President Donald Trump earlier this year issued the first warning by raising taxes on major Chinese export products, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation was announced this week when new effective, increased tax rates were unveiled for $200 billion (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150 billion) in goods; half of all goods coming from China to the US.
Beijing has taken reprisals in kind each time, most recently by raising tariffs from 5 to 10% for $60 billion in U.S. goods.
China has vowed to match the U.S. every time, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to blink.
In order for Washington to bow, requests must be granted, but public bowing for the US is far too painful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts argue that if Beijing plays smart, the trade war with the US could positively support China in the longer term, as the mutual dependence of the two economies decreases.
"The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that could result in one of the two countries falling into an economic free fall is actually much more dangerous than spectators have previously acknowledged," said Abigail Grace, a researcher at the Center for a New American Security (CNS) research center.
Syria 'ready' to return refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country that has been devastated by a war lasting more than seven years.
During his speech to the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem declared that conditions in his country are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas devastated by terrorists, and to normalize the situation on the ground.
All circumstances are now present for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that threatened their daily lives and existence.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled their country since the war began in 2011.
It is estimated that there are about six million people in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome assistance in restoring the devastated country.
However, he stressed that Syria would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from countries that had subsidized the uprising.
