Red glow update: Concentrations decline in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota provinces
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decrease in concentrations of Red Glory in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the committee, there are reports of a fragmentary increase in the red glow in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County to see spots, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow has also been seen in Pasco County.
There have been medium concentrations reported for the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations for the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or for the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or for the coast of Le County.
Irritation of the airways in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier is continuously reported.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in northwest Florida in the past week.
